commitResults.messageTitle: Add Name class, Show class, and Tag class
commitResults.messageBody:
Modify the original address book class to fit Trackermon.

1. Create Name class to represent name of show.
2. Create Show class to represent shows within Trackermon
3. Create Tag class to represent tags of the show.

This provides a layer of abstraction allowing us to abstract away lower
level details. For example, the toString method of Show case would
return the string representation of the Show class.

Going to add a status component into the Show class in the future
iteration.

This will help us to catch certain runtime errors that may occur.
1. DuplicatedShowException is thrown when there is a duplicated shows.
2. ShowNotFoundException is thrown when no show can be found.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update Find command to handle fragmented show names
commitResults.messageBody:
Updated find command to handle fragmented words because the user might key in an incomplete word in the command line but still expect a result to be shown.

Creating a new method in StringUtil.java allows us to handle these fragmented words. For example, containsFragmentedWordIgnoreCase("ABc def", "AB") == true.

It is done this way so as to handle fragmented words being able to be found in the category to be searched in.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update Find command to handle status and tags
commitResults.messageBody:
Updated find command to be able to search for status and tags. In addition, updated find to include searching via prefixes. E.g., find [n/NAME] [s/STATUS] [t/TAGS].

Extending the current classes like FindCommandParser and creating a new class like ShowContainsKeywordsPredicate allow us to implement a better search function as mentioned above.

It is done this way so as to allow the user to have an easier time to find the show name/status/tags he/she desires.
Changed the code to be slightly more efficient.

Updated the Help Window to show a command summary of all the commands in Trackermon with its syntax because the user might forget what are the commands and wants a quick look at the commands without going into the user guide.

Creating a CommandBuilder class in ui package, a Stackpane in SceneBuilder, and updating HelpWindow.java allows us to create a TableView of the command summary and display to the user.

It is done this way so as to give the user quick access to the commands available on top of having the user guide.

It is done this way so as to give the user more flexibility to find the exact show he/she wants in the show list.
